#hm-note[
  Plant work in Year One uses the *first and second degrees almost exclusively.*
  Do not reach for higher heat than necessary. More damage has been done to spagyric
  preparations by impatient overheating than by any other single error.

  If a student has access only to a domestic kitchen stove with an electric burner,
  a glass bain-marie (double boiler) on its lowest setting is a perfectly adequate
  water bath. If they have a small electric hotplate, that is even better — precise
  temperature control is worth far more than a large or elaborate setup.
]

*The Ideal Menstruum.* For maximum potency, the ideal liquid for spagyric extraction
is the *distilled water taken from the plant itself* — either collected by dragging a
linen sheet across dew-laden Melissa before dawn, or condensed from the moisture
released during the plant's own gentle dehydration. This "plant water" carries the
plant's Mercury in its most natural and uncontaminated form.

Rectified spirits of wine is the practical alternative for most students, and is
entirely valid. The traditional test for sufficient rectification is the *Cotton Wick
Test*: dip a cotton wick into the spirit and set it alight. If the flame fastens on
the wick itself and burns it cleanly, the spirit is sufficiently dephlegmated.
If it does not hold the flame on the wick, the alcohol is too dilute and must be
rectified further. This test is non-negotiable — impure menstruum is one of the four
primary causes of failed first-year preparations.

*Melissa officinalis — The First Herb.* Lemon Balm has been chosen by practitioners
across traditions as the gateway herb for several reasons: it is gentle, widely
available, carries a distinct and pleasant Sulphur signature, and responds clearly to
basic spagyric treatment. It belongs to *Jupiter* in planetary rulership (secondarily
solar), is associated historically with spiritual elevation, clarity of mind, and
the restoration of the vital spirit after exhaustion.

#doctrine[
