  obtained, responds well to maceration, and produces a clear and instructive
  calcination. The student who has made a genuine Melissa spagyric has learned
  everything that the first year needs to teach in miniature."_
  #align(right)[— HAB (Bartlett Prima transcript), paraphrased]
]

*Planetary Timing.* Begin operations during the *planetary hour of Jupiter* for
maximum alignment with the plant's virtue. Jupiter's day is Thursday. Jupiter's hours
rotate through the day in a fixed sequence calculated from sunrise. (The headmaster
provides or directs the student to a planetary hours calculator.) This is not
superstition — it is the timing of the work to the cosmic pattern that governs the
plant's essential character, in the same way that a sailor times departure to the
tide.

*Alternative Plants.* If Melissa is genuinely unavailable:
- *Lavender* (flowers) — responds well to steam distillation; ruled by Mercury
- *Caraway* (seeds) — yields fixed salts easier for the Tyro to handle; ruled by Mercury
- *Rosemary* — primary alternative for practising the separation of the Three Essentials; ruled by the Sun

#lab[
  *The Maceration — Week 3 Protocol*

  + *Source the herb.* Dried whole Melissa officinalis is preferred. Obtain from a
    reputable herb supplier; avoid capsule products or tea bags. If you can grow and
    dry your own, do so — the relationship with the living plant is part of the work.
  + *Prepare the menstruum.* Rectified spirits of wine (190-proof grain alcohol,
    Everclear, or equivalent, OR high-proof brandy for the seven-fold distillation
    method — see AH Ch. III). Run the Cotton Wick Test before use.
  + *Grind the dried herb* in the mortar. Grinding releases the Sulphur by bruising
    the plant tissue; coarse grinding is sufficient. Do not reduce to powder — chunks
    of roughly 5mm are ideal.
  + *Fill the flask one-third* with ground herb. Do not pack tightly.
  + *Cover with menstruum.* Pour until the herb is fully submerged with at least
    2cm of liquid above the surface.
  + *Seal tightly* with a well-fitted stopper. Wrap with parafilm if available.
  + *Label the flask* with: date, plant name, menstruum used, planetary hour and day
    of beginning.
  + *Place in gentle warmth* — water bath temperature, or a warm dark shelf above
    a radiator. Shade from direct sunlight.
  + *The maceration begins.* It will sit for weeks. Leave it alone.

  *Four Common Errors — Memorise Before Beginning:*

  + *Lost ingress through vitrification* — the most specific and most damaging Year
    One error. Calcination temperature for Melissa must not exceed *400°C*. Above
    this threshold, the plant salts melt and fuse, glazing into a glassy mass
    incapable of absorbing the essence during cohobation. A glazed salt is alchemically
    inert. Calcine slowly, in stages, grinding between each.
  + *Impure menstruum* — using spirits that have not passed the Cotton Wick Test.
    The second most common error and entirely avoidable.
  + *Mixing kingdoms* — vegetable essence must never be combined with mineral or
    animal salts. Each kingdom operates at a distinct vibratory rate. The result is
    not a failed preparation — it is no preparation at all.
  + *Luting leaks* — small silent leaks in the vessel's seal during long digestions
    allow volatile fractions to escape. Check seals at every session. If you can
    smell your preparation from outside the vessel, it is leaking.
]

=== Topics This Week

- The laboratory as sacred space: attention as the primary instrument
- The four degrees of fire: when each is used in Year One
- The Cotton Wick Test: a non-negotiable quality check for the menstruum
- Rectifying spirits of wine: the seven-fold method (AH Ch. III)
- Melissa officinalis: planetary rulership, medicinal history, and why it is chosen
- The ideal menstruum: plant's own dew-water vs. rectified spirits
- Maceration protocol: vessel, proportion, seal, labelling, temperature
- The four common errors: memorise before touching anything
- Alternative herbs if Melissa is unavailable

#inner-work[
  *The Inner Flame & Laboratory Consecration*

  This week add the inner flame practice to the daily sitting. After the Third Eye
  Focus and the Threefold Breath, settle into stillness and form — in the mind's eye,
  or simply as a felt sense — the image of a small flame burning quietly in the centre
  of the body. Below the ribs, above the pelvis: the place instinctively felt as the
  body's centre.

  This flame does not burn or harm; it is the vital fire itself — the Secret Fire
  that the tradition says is present in all living things and in the mineral kingdom
  as well. As you breathe, notice the flame. When the mind wanders, return to it —
  not with effort but with simple attention, as you might glance back at a candle in
  a room you were leaving.

  *Before entering the laboratory* each session: spend three minutes with this flame.
  Let it be the same fire you are working with externally. Over time, the inner and
  outer fire will begin to feel like one thing.

  *Consecrate the laboratory space* this week. Sit in silence within it for at least
  twenty minutes before doing any practical work. Bring nothing but your attention.
  Ask honestly: what am I bringing into this space? What intention am I carrying into
  the Work?
]

